The maximum inradius for a tangential quadrilateral with given side lengths is achieved when the quadrilateral is also cyclic, which maximizes the area. For sides \(AB=2\), \(BC=3\), \(CD=5\), and \(DA=4\), the semiperimeter is \(s=7\), and the product of the sides is \(abcd = 120\). The area of the cyclic quadrilateral is \(\sqrt{abcd} = 2\sqrt{30}\), so the inradius is \(r = \frac{2\sqrt{30}}{7}\).

